The suburb in the south of Johannesburg has been plagued by organised crime and illegal brothels. JOHANNESBURG - The Democratic Alliance says it has received confirmation from the Independent Police Investigative Directorate (Ipid) that it will investigate the Rosettenville South African Police Service (SAPS) after community outrage at alleged police involvement in crime in the area. The suburb south of Johannesburg has been plagued by organised crime and illegal brothels. Last month, several houses belonging to foreign nationals were set alight by locals who claimed the properties were being used for criminal purposes. Residents say they decided to take the law into their own hands after police failed to follow up on reported cases.&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:12.0pt;line-height:107%;font-family: &quot;Century Gothic&quot;,sans-serif&quot;&gt;WATCH: Rosettenville on knife s edge over drugs and brothels in areaThe DA has welcomed the investigation and called for officers found to be involved in crime to be dismissed so Rosettenville can be cleaned up.The party's Kate Lorimer says: We have received many clips that indicate members of the SAPS are involved. We believe crooked cops are made an example of. It is a real opportunity for us to do something about it and expose crooked cops. (Edited by Shimoney Regter)